<li id="cite_note-:8-13"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-:8_13-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-:8_13-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1133582631"><cite id="CITEREFAhmad" class="citation web cs1">Ahmad, Tufail. <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.firstpost.com/long-reads/indias-ex-muslims-3274246.html">"India's ex-Muslims"</a>. <i>Firstpost</i><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">31 July</span> 2020</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Firstpost&amp;rft.atitle=India%27s+ex-Muslims&amp;rft.aulast=Ahmad&amp;rft.aufirst=Tufail&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.firstpost.com%2Flong-reads%2Findias-ex-muslims-3274246.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AEx-Muslims" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-14"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-14">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1133582631"><cite id="CITEREFAl_Zidjaly2019" class="citation journal cs1">Al Zidjaly, Najma (2019). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://research.tilburguniversity.edu/en/publications/digital-activism-as-nexus-analysis-a-sociolinguistic-example-from">"Digital activism as nexus analysis:: A sociolinguistic example from Arabic Twitter"</a>. <i>Tilburg Papers in Culture Studies</i> (221). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20210715122429/https://pure.uvt.nl/ws/portalfiles/portal/48994895/TPCS_221_Al_Zidjaly.pdf">Archived</a> <span class="cs1-format">(PDF)</span> from the original on 15 July 2021 &#8211; via research.tilburguniversity.edu. <q>..the Ex-Muslim community, the community is heterogeneous, consisting of members with differing degrees of belief. Some key members are celebrated intellectuals from Kuwait and Saudi Arabia who do not admit to leaving Islam, but rather construct themselves as humanists, liberals and/or secularists. Separation of religion and politics by questioning Islamic authoritative discourses (albeit to a lesser degree than self-admitted Ex-Muslims) is the goal. .. Those who self-identify as Quranics, who believe only in the teachings of the Quran and reject all other Islamic teachings, also constitute members of the community. Therefore, they and the liberals are positioned as covert Ex-Muslims.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Tilburg+Papers+in+Culture+Studies&amp;rft.atitle=Digital+activism+as+nexus+analysis%3A%3A+A+sociolinguistic+example+from+Arabic+Twitter&amp;rft.issue=221&amp;rft.date=2019&amp;rft.aulast=Al+Zidjaly&amp;rft.aufirst=Najma&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fresearch.tilburguniversity.edu%2Fen%2Fpublications%2Fdigital-activism-as-nexus-analysis-a-sociolinguistic-example-from&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AEx-Muslims" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-15"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-15">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1133582631"><cite id="CITEREFAl_Zidjaly2019" class="citation journal cs1">Al Zidjaly, Najma (2019). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://research.tilburguniversity.edu/en/publications/digital-activism-as-nexus-analysis-a-sociolinguistic-example-from">"Digital activism as nexus analysis:: A sociolinguistic example from Arabic Twitter"</a>. <i>Tilburg Papers in Culture Studies</i> (221). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20210715122429/https://pure.uvt.nl/ws/portalfiles/portal/48994895/TPCS_221_Al_Zidjaly.pdf">Archived</a> <span class="cs1-format">(PDF)</span> from the original on 15 July 2021 &#8211; via research.tilburguniversity.edu. <q>.. who do not admit to leaving Islam, but rather construct themselves as humanists, liberals and/or secularists. Separation of religion and politics by questioning Islamic authoritative discourses (albeit to a lesser degree than self-admitted Ex-Muslims) is the goal. Those who self-identify as Quranics, who believe only in the teachings of the Quran and reject all other Islamic teachings, also constitute members of the community. Therefore, they and the liberals are positioned as covert Ex-Muslims. ..</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Tilburg+Papers+in+Culture+Studies&amp;rft.atitle=Digital+activism+as+nexus+analysis%3A%3A+A+sociolinguistic+example+from+Arabic+Twitter&amp;rft.issue=221&amp;rft.date=2019&amp;rft.aulast=Al+Zidjaly&amp;rft.aufirst=Najma&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fresearch.tilburguniversity.edu%2Fen%2Fpublications%2Fdigital-activism-as-nexus-analysis-a-sociolinguistic-example-from&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AEx-Muslims" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-:04-16"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-:04_16-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-:04_16-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1133582631"><cite id="CITEREFHassan2022" class="citation web cs1">Hassan, Farzana (1 July 2022). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://torontosun.com/opinion/columnists/hassan-the-ex-muslim-movement-seeks-to-challenge-apostasy-in-islam">"HASSAN: The ex-Muslim movement seeks to challenge apostasy in Islam"</a>. <i>torontosun</i>. <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20210701210905/https://torontosun.com/opinion/columnists/hassan-the-ex-muslim-movement-seeks-to-challenge-apostasy-in-islam">Archived</a> from the original on 1 July 2022<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">6 May</span> 2022</span>. <q>.. it is because of fear of ostracism from close family, friends, and the community that many ex-Muslims hide their non-belief. Relationships are important to individuals, and close relations that much more. Unless family units leave Islam en masse — and this has certainly happened — individuals who belong to very religious families, or even moderately religious families, are often forced to lead double lives. Many can accomplish this by being "cultural Muslims," partaking in all the outward observances of religion while keeping their disbelief to themselves. ..</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=torontosun&amp;rft.atitle=HASSAN%3A+The+ex-Muslim+movement+seeks+to+challenge+apostasy+in+Islam&amp;rft.date=2022-07-01&amp;rft.aulast=Hassan&amp;rft.aufirst=Farzana&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Ftorontosun.com%2Fopinion%2Fcolumnists%2Fhassan-the-ex-muslim-movement-seeks-to-challenge-apostasy-in-islam&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AEx-Muslims" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-17"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-17">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1133582631"><cite id="CITEREFAl_Zidjaly2019" class="citation journal cs1">Al Zidjaly, Najma (2019). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://research.tilburguniversity.edu/en/publications/digital-activism-as-nexus-analysis-a-sociolinguistic-example-from">"Digital activism as nexus analysis:: A sociolinguistic example from Arabic Twitter"</a>. <i>Tilburg Papers in Culture Studies</i> (221). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20210715122429/https://pure.uvt.nl/ws/portalfiles/portal/48994895/TPCS_221_Al_Zidjaly.pdf">Archived</a> <span class="cs1-format">(PDF)</span> from the original on 15 July 2021 &#8211; via research.tilburguniversity.edu. <q>.. Notably, the Arab social media report (Salem, 2017) illustrates that Saudis are the most active Arabs on Twitter, suggesting that Saudi women and men overcome their ostensible lack of agency through technology (especially WhatsApp, Facebook and Twitter), in which realm they have covertly played key roles in leading the religiously strict Arabian Gulf countries towards change. ..</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Tilburg+Papers+in+Culture+Studies&amp;rft.atitle=Digital+activism+as+nexus+analysis%3A%3A+A+sociolinguistic+example+from+Arabic+Twitter&amp;rft.issue=221&amp;rft.date=2019&amp;rft.aulast=Al+Zidjaly&amp;rft.aufirst=Najma&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fresearch.tilburguniversity.edu%2Fen%2Fpublications%2Fdigital-activism-as-nexus-analysis-a-sociolinguistic-example-from&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AEx-Muslims" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-18"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-18">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1133582631"><cite id="CITEREFBurge2021" class="citation web cs1">Burge, Ryan (7 July 2021). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://religionnews.com/2021/07/07/exmna-the-cost-of-leaving-islam-for-american-muslims/">"The high cost of becoming a none for American Muslims"</a>. <i>Religion News Service</i>. <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20210707233556/https://religionnews.com/2021/07/07/exmna-the-cost-of-leaving-islam-for-american-muslims/">Archived</a> from the original on 7 July 2021<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">6 May</span> 2022</span>. <q>.. The data also makes clear that leaving a religion is more than ending certain ways of life. It leads to a cascade of implications that can impact all aspects of the apostate's life, often negatively, and often most powerfully in their relationships. ..  Two-thirds of EXMNA respondents reported that they hid their deconversion from some people in their lives, while 62% said that they lost friendships. Forty-five percent of the sample indicated that they had been ostracized by some members of their family, and 30% said that they lost financial support as well. ..</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Religion+News+Service&amp;rft.atitle=The+high+cost+of+becoming+a+none+for+American+Muslims&amp;rft.date=2021-07-07&amp;rft.aulast=Burge&amp;rft.aufirst=Ryan&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Freligionnews.com%2F2021%2F07%2F07%2Fexmna-the-cost-of-leaving-islam-for-american-muslims%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AEx-Muslims" class="Z3988"></span></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-:10-19"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-:10_19-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-:10_19-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-:10_19-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1133582631"><cite id="CITEREFOrensteinWeismann2016" class="citation journal cs1">Orenstein, Ziv; Weismann, Itzchak (1 October 2016). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://doi.org/10.1080/09596410.2016.1148892">"Neither Muslim nor Other: British Secular Muslims"</a>. <i>Islam and Christian–Muslim Relations</i>. <b>27</b> (4): 379–395. <a href="/wiki/Doi_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="Doi (identifier)">doi</a>:<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://doi.org/10.1080%2F09596410.2016.1148892">10.1080/09596410.2016.1148892</a>. <a href="/wiki/ISSN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISSN (identifier)">ISSN</a>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.worldcat.org/issn/0959-6410">0959-6410</a>. <a href="/wiki/S2CID_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="S2CID (identifier)">S2CID</a>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://api.semanticscholar.org/CorpusID:147266809">147266809</a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Islam+and+Christian%E2%80%93Muslim+Relations&amp;rft.atitle=Neither+Muslim+nor+Other%3A+British+Secular+Muslims&amp;rft.volume=27&amp;rft.issue=4&amp;rft.pages=379-395&amp;rft.date=2016-10-01&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fapi.semanticscholar.org%2FCorpusID%3A147266809%23id-name%3DS2CID&amp;rft.issn=0959-6410&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1080%2F09596410.2016.1148892&amp;rft.aulast=Orenstein&amp;rft.aufirst=Ziv&amp;rft.au=Weismann%2C+Itzchak&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fdoi.org%2F10.1080%2F09596410.2016.1148892&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AEx-Muslims" class="Z3988"></span></span>
